</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=glatius2>Glatius2</A> at: 1/29/03 12:20:10 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ketherami>Kether Am I</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 17<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/29/03 12:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2829.topic&index=26>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Under Review Maybe they are listening</span><hr size=1> I have played paladin and cleric in PoV/PoS/BoT zones.  This is from direct personal experience. <br>
<br>
As cleric I don't care which tank class our group takes.  ANY of them played competently works.  What differs is how you have to adjust.  A knight tanking allows for faster debuffing but means you have to be sharper with the MT heals.  A warrior tanking means you have to be more cautious with early debuffs and heals, but you can ride out the CHs longer.<br>
<br>
Yes, 61st level warriors with few AAs and RoK weapons are going to suck.  But I am going to inform you: 61st knights with few AAs and RoK armor SUCK as well.<br>
<br>
A good portion of the 'problem' is honestly shear laziness of group members.  Yes, Enchanter_01 it is NOT a good idea to tash before the warrior even hits the mob.  There is no reason to.  IF you tank is that bad that it needs the mob slowed in under 10s then the tank SHOULDN'T be tanking that mob.  Honestly, my preferred pickup tank is a blue (warlords I am guessing) armored warrior with a Windblade.  I don't recall his name, but he know how to play and work with the group.<br>
<br>
I think a *mild* correction to warrior aggro is in order.  Something that gives them a tad bit of +Hate at the engage with a relatively short reuse.  Nothing to rival EB aggro, just something to help during those first 10s of a fight.  To give them knight or better aggro would ruin the game.  It would give the best defensive tank class the best aggro.  No one takes a second tank for 'damage' if other options are available, and almost no one considers other non-stacking attributes such as paladin healing.<br>
<br>
As is warrior pure melee dps is greater than knights (yes, assuming equivalent gear/AAs).  Right now a additive warrior (even if not desired) brings more DPS than a paladin.  If tank aggro is made nearly identical then you run across the prospect of needing to adjust knight melee abilities upwards so they can fill an additive roll better.<br>
<br>
My ideal would be:<br>
<br>
Warrior: workable aggro, best tanking skills, more HP, baseline 1.0 melee DPS, useful disciplines<br>
Paladin: best aggro, good tanking skills, less HP, 0.8 melee DPS, emergency healing<br>
<br>
Basically, if you pump up warrior aggro to &quot;its not a problem anymore&quot; levels then I forsee a raising of knight skill caps so that their offense is more akin to 0.9.  This is somewhat problematic though since SK spells being offensive in nature generally 'stack' well with a group.  Perhaps simply giving paladins some cleric DDs would help since then they could use their mana to do something iteratively helpful as well.  A fast-casting version of the level 44 clr nuke would probably work.  One of the above honestly may be what they have in mind already though.   <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ketherami>Kether Am I</A> at: 1/29/03 12:23:58 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=frodlin7th>Frodlin7th</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>is a Seasoned Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 285<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/29/03 12:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2829.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Under Review Maybe they are listening</span><hr size=1> Grendon, <br>
<br>
I did a &quot;taunt test&quot; last night vs. an Imperial guard in Ssra, since we were screwing around waiting for Blood to pop.    Many warriors on the serveride channel saw this because I was becoming increasingly frustrated as time went on.<br>
<br>
When taunt works, the mob turns to you period.   This was verified by the mob turning and beating on me when it did work.<br>
<br>
So, here's the deal.... I stood next to a mob who was being killed.   I sat there and hit the taunt button.  Did nothing else to generate aggro, no attack on no ranged attacks, no nothing, just press taunt.<br>
<br>
After doing it 77 times in a row, with no attention from the mob, I was wondering exactly what was the problem.   I wondered if those mobs wee simply taunt immune, or if the way we all thought about taunt was wrong.... on the 78th time, it worked.   On the 81st time, it worked.... on the 92nd time, it worked.    This meant that.... the mobs WERENT immune, and that it DID work the way we all thought it did (auto to top of hate list) but that the rate of it working was stupidly low.<br>
<br>
Before you say &quot;gee, there had to be a string of bad luck... let's say for the sake of argument that taunt is 50% reliable.... Go flip a quarter, you have a 50% chance of heads or tails... flip it 77 times in a row, and tell me if you get heads each time.     The odds of this happenning are so low that a number cannot be made to represent this possibility.   You have a higher chance of being struck by lightning on a clear day while indoors.<br>
<br>
