<br>
1. A warrior has no real control over aggro other than to engage a random number generator and accept the results.<br>
<br>
2. Every other class DOES have a way to control (or at least to some degree) aggro generation.<br>
<br>
Now, having said that, I still disagree with your conclusion that the mitigation difference between Knights and Warriors compensates in terms of mana/effort spent for at will aggro generation.   The reson I say this is because of the cost of ancillary heals.  They are exactly the same as Complete heals, barring mana conservation focus items, which do work on shorter cast time heals and not CH, but this number isn't large.<br>
<br>
In reality the ratio of CH's needed between a knight and a warrior (this is considering no heals or taps are cast by the knight) is approximately 11 to 10.   In other words, a warrior needs 10 CH's to equal 11 CH's roughly for a Knight.    <br>
<br>
The question is, in 10 CH's to a warrior, if another party member gets hit more than once, the mana savings is in favor of the Knight, the more lost aggro on the part of the warrior, the more favorable the Knight becomes.<br>
<br>
I'd say that it's roughly 2:1 in my experience as a warrior with high aggro weapons, and 8300hp group buffed.  In other words, for every 2 CH's performed on me, at least one party member needs a small heal.   <br>
<br>
So, for every 10 CH's preformed on me, it's really 15  CH's worth of mana.    For a Knight, it would be 11 CH's worth of mana, meaning that the Knight represents a rather large mana cost savings to a group. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=frodlin7th>Frodlin7th</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>is a Seasoned Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 287<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/29/03 2:10 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2829.topic&index=33>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Under Review Maybe they are listening</span><hr size=1> Madrone,<br>
<br>
I agree, and it was done in High Ssra (at emp portal) which has many coding issues which differ from PoP (no charm, Mez, yadda yadda).    I'm not trying to state that this is definitive results of taunt working, but I would use it to point to the fact that taunt is indeed unreliable, (i.e. cannot be trusted as a primary method of aggro generation) and is still really out of the control of the warrior.   Worse, outside of a few intelligent mobs, who give a taunt success message, we have know way of gauging it's effectiveness.   Every other class who casts spells knows when they have been fully or partially resisted, and even a precise number of how much damage they do.   The warrior (and any other class who uses the Taunt button) has no way to gauge the success of their attempts, particulrly if they're on or near the top of their aggro list.<br>
<br>
Finally, since taunt is, under most peoples' experience (and Abashi's admission) a technique of transferring aggro, and not one of generating it, they have no way of quantifying or controlling the quantity of aggro that they generate, other than melee damage, which we can mostly agree is rather on the low side comparatively, whereas every other class (outside of monks and rogues) can say to themselves &quot;If I repeat this behaviour, it will generate X number of aggro higher than the guy who has done pervious behaviours.&quot;<br>
<br>
